# boot/cmdline.txt.patch
#
# /boot/cmdline.txt is a SINGLE-LINE file — appending would break it.
# bootstrap.sh must INSERT the token "modules-load=dwc2" immediately after
# "rootwait" on that one line, then write the file back.
#
# Purpose: instruct the kernel to load the dwc2 USB-gadget driver during
# early boot, before any service manager starts. This is required for the
# ipod-gadget modules to bind to the USB OTG controller at boot time.
#
# Reference: CLAUDE.md § "USB role"
#   modules-load=dwc2 must appear after rootwait in /boot/cmdline.txt
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Idempotent sed one-liner used by bootstrap.sh
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# The substitution fires only when "modules-load=dwc2" is NOT already present
# (the /! guard), so running bootstrap.sh twice is safe.
#
#   sed -i '/modules-load=dwc2/! s/\brootwait\b/rootwait modules-load=dwc2/' /boot/cmdline.txt
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Manual-edit example
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# BEFORE (typical Raspberry Pi OS Lite 64-bit default):
#   console=serial0,115200 console=tty1 root=PARTUUID=xxxxxxxx-02 rootfstype=ext4 fsck.repair=yes rootwait quiet init=/usr/lib/raspberrypi-sys-mods/firstboot
#
# AFTER (with dwc2 inserted immediately after rootwait):
#   console=serial0,115200 console=tty1 root=PARTUUID=xxxxxxxx-02 rootfstype=ext4 fsck.repair=yes rootwait modules-load=dwc2 quiet init=/usr/lib/raspberrypi-sys-mods/firstboot
#
# Notes:
#   - Keep everything on a single line — do NOT introduce newlines.
#   - The PARTUUID value is unique to your SD card; the example above is
#     illustrative only.
#   - "quiet" and trailing tokens stay in place; only "rootwait" gains a
#     suffix token.
